<li> <h4><a name="setting">Setting <i>"spider"</i> Command</a></h4>

You can define an alias for your <i>SPIDER</i> executable's location. 
If you are
using the <i>'C'</i> shell, you would put a line similar to the
following in the <i>.cshrc</i> startup file in your home directory:

   <blockquote>
   <kbd>
   alias spider PARENT_DIR/spider/bin/spider_linux_mp_intel
   </kbd>
   </blockquote>

Alternatively, you can modify your executable search <i>path</i> so that your system
can locate the executable file when you type "spider". To alter
your path (if you are using the <i>'C'</i> shell) add the following 
to the <i>PATH</i> environmental variable in your 
<i>.cshrc</i> startup
file: <br>
<br>
 
<p>
If <i>PATH</i> is not already set in your startup file add the
following line to your <i>.cshrc</i> startup file</dt>
   <blockquote>
   <kbd>
   set path= PARENT_DIR/spider/bin
   </kbd>
   </blockquote>
</p>

<p>
If PATH is already set in your startup file, add the following line 
 to your <i>.cshrc</i> startup file
   <blockquote>
   <kbd>
   set path=($path PARENT_DIR/spider/bin)
   </kbd>
   </blockquote>
</p>
Then rename the desired <i>spider_linux</i> executable in PARENT_DIR/spider/bin to:
<i>spider</i>. 
d211 1
a211 1
<p></p>
d213 3
a215 1
<li> <h4><a name="setenv">Setting environment variables</a></h4>
d217 2
a218 4
You will also need to tell <i>SPIDER</i> the location of your
manual pages and SPIDER system procedure files. If you are using
the <i>'C'</i> shell, you should place following lines in your
<i>.cshrc</i> startup file: 
d220 3
a222 7
<blockquote><kbd>
   setenv SPMAN_DIR  "PARENT_DIR/spider/man/"<br>
   setenv SPPROC_DIR "PARENT_DIR/spider/proc/"<br>
</kbd></blockquote>
</li>

<p></p>
a223 1
</ul>
a225 1
<li> <h3><a name="run">RUNNING SPIDER</a></h3>
d227 3
a229 1
<p>Run SPIDER in a terminal window:</p>
d231 30
a260 5
<blockquote>
   <dl>
   <dt><kbd>spider three-character-data-extension </kbd></dt>
   </dl>
</blockquote>
d262 1
a262 33
<p>All SPIDER data files will have the three-character-data-extension (or
   datacode) added automatically inside SPIDER.</p>

<p>The SPIDER "RESULTS" files are named <i>results.ext.?</i> where
   "?" is incremented for existing results file in that directory.</p>

<p>SPIDER can be run in the background or submitted as a 
   <a href= "batch-unix_doc.html">batch</a> using the UNIX <i>"at"</i>
   command.</p>

<p>If SPIDER does not run and you get an error message like:  
   <i>command not found</i> see 
   "<a href="#setting">Setting <i>'spider'</i> command</a>" 
   above to ensure that your desired executable is
   accessible.</p> 

<p>If SPIDER does not start running and you
   get a error message about a missing library, then you are missing one
   or more run-time (shared) libraries. Check your <i>LD_LIBRARY_PATH</i> 
  environment variable. The executables distributed with SPIDER are
  mostly linked statically so this should not be a problem with them.</p> 

<p>If SPIDER complains about the 'Nextresults' script which increments
   the Results file version number then your Linux distribution (e.g.
   Ubuntu) may have a non-standard sort operation.  Try replacing <br>
      <dd><i> lastfi=`(\ls $1.[0-9]* | sort -t. +2n | tail -1)` </i></dd><br>
   with   <br>
      <dd><i> lastfi=`(\ls $1.[0-9]* | sort -t. -k2 -n | tail -1)`</i></dd><br>
  in spider/man/Nextresults. </p> 

<p>If SPIDER still does not run please contact us at the address
   below. Please send complete info on what you are trying to do, error
   messages, screen dump, etc.</p>
a273 5
<li> <h3><a name="testing">TESTING SPIDER</a></h3>
   Some <a href="testing.html">simple tests</a> are available to see
   if SPIDER is operating correctly.
</li>

d278 3
a280 2
trying to do, including relevant results files, procedure files,
and error messages. 
d284 3
a286 3
