    <li>  <A href="#bugs">          BUGS</a> </li>
d28 86
d115 69
a183 1
<ol>
d186 8
a193 1
    <h3><a name="loading">LOADING THE DISTRIBUTION </a></h3>
d195 2
a196 38
    Code is distributed by <i>ftp</i> in tar format or on CD-ROM in 
    ISO-9660 format.  The distribution takes about 176 Mb of disk 
    space but includes libraries and 
    executables for different systems.  Only about 17Mb is necessary
    for a single operating system.  To load SPIDER use the 
    following commands:

    <blockquote> 
    <kbd>
    <dl>
    <dt>cd PARENT-DIR
    <dd>(where PARENT-DIR is parent of desired location of SPIDER)
    <DT><i>mkdir spider</i>  
    <dd>(creates a new sub-directory for SPIDER,
         hereafter referred to as SPIDER_DIR)

    <dt> From <i>ftp</i> delivery:
       <dl>
       <dt><i>tar xvf "ftp_filename" spider</i> 
       </dl>

    <dt> From CDROM:
       <dl>
       <dt><i>cp -r "your_cdrom_device"/spider/* spider</i>  
       </dl>
    </dl>
    </kbd></blockquote> 
    <p>
    The following directories will be created:               <br>
   
    <table border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="4">
    <tr> <th halign="left">Directory</th> <th halign="left">Contents</th> </tr> 
    <tr><td>SPIDER-DIR/src</td><td>source code, SPIDER libraries</td></tr>
    <tr><td>SPIDER-DIR/bin</td><td>executables</td></tr>
    <tr><td>SPIDER-DIR/docs</td><td>documentation, html pages</td></tr>
    <tr><td>SPIDER-DIR/proc</td><td>Sample procedure files</td></tr>
    <tr><td>SPIDER-DIR/man</td><td>ASCII documentation, Nextresults</td></tr>  
    </table>
a197 1
</p>
a198 1
<p>
d200 1
a200 40
    <h3><a name="installation"> INSTALLATION</a></h3>
    <ul> 
    <li> <h4>Executables</h4>
    The <i>SPIDER_DIR/bin</i> directory should contain the following
            GNU-Linux executable files:  

    <p>  
    <table border="3" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="5">  
    <tr><th>SPIDER</th>             <th>optimal<br>processor</th> <th>optimal<br>byte order</th> <th>FFTW shared<br>libraries</th> </tr>
    <tr><td>spider_linux_mp</td>             <td>AMD 32</td>                 <td> SGI</td>           <td>none</td> </tr> 
    <tr><td>spider_linux_mpfftw</td>         <td>AMD 32</td>                 <td> SGI</td>           <td><a href="./fftw.html"> FFTW</a></td>  </tr> 
    <tr><td>spider_linux_mpfftw_rh7</td>     <td>AMD 32</td>                 <td> SGI</td>           <td><a href="./fftw.html"> FFTW</a></td>  </tr> 
    <tr><td>spider_linux_mpfftw_intel</td>   <td>Intel 32</td>               <td> SGI</td>           <td><a href="./fftw.html"> FFTW</a></td>  </tr> 
    <tr><td>spider_linux_mpfftw_altix</td>   <td>Itanium2</td>               <td> SGI</td>           <td><a href="./fftw.html"> FFTW</a></td>   </tr> 
    </table>
   </p>

   <p>

    <li> <h4><a>FFTW Libraries</a> </h4>
      All the GNU-Linux SPIDER executables except: <i>spider_linux_mp</i> 
         need to link with shared, run-time
         FFTW libraries.  If these are not already present in your system 
         you will have to <a href="./fftw.html">install FFTW</a>.

         You will also need to tell <i>SPIDER</i> the location of the shared 
         FFTW libraries (<a href="#loading">Setting environment variables</a>) 
    </li>
    <p>

    <li>
      <h3><a name="compiling">Compiling and Linking SPIDER.</a></h3>
      If you wish to modify SPIDER source code, link SPIDER
      with different libraries, or compile SPIDER with different compilation 
      options (e.g. optimize speed for your processors) you will have to 
      have a Fortran 90 compiler on your system.  
      See <a href="compile-linux.html">SPIDER Compilation and Linking on GNU-Linux</a>
      documentation for further information.
    </li>
    <p>
d202 14
a215 1
    <li> <h4><a name="setting">Setting <i>"spider"</i> Command</a> </h4>
d217 23
a239 66
      You can define an alias for your <i>SPIDER</i> location.  If you 
      are  using the  <i>'C'</i> shell, you would put a line similar to 
      the  following in the <i>.cshrc</i> startup file in your home directory:

        <blockquote>  <kbd>
                alias  spider    SPIDER_DIR/spider_linux_mpfftw  <br>
        </kbd> </blockquote>

      Alternatively, you can modify your path so that your 
      your system can locate the executable file when you type 
      "spider". To alter your path using the <i>'C'</i> shell add the following 
        to the  <i>PATH</i> environmental variable in your <i>.cshrc</i> startup file: 
        </p>
        <dl> 
        <dt> If <i>PATH</i> is not already set in your startup file add
              the following line to your <i>.cshrc</i> startup file</dt>
        <dd> set path= SPIDER_DIR</dd>
        </p>
        <dt>If <i>PATH</i> is already set in your startup file add
              the following line to your <i>.cshrc</i> startup file</dt>
        <dd> set path=($path SPIDER_DIR)</dd>
        </dl>
        </p>
        then rename the <I>spider_linux</I> executable in SPIDER_DIR to: <i>spider</i>. <P>
    </li>
    <p>


   <li><h4><a name="setenv">Setting environment variables</a></h4>

         You will also need to tell <i>SPIDER</i> the location of your manual pages and
         SPIDER system procedure files.  If you are using the 
         <i>'C'</i> shell, you should place following lines in 
         your <i>.cshrc</i> startup file (replace SPIDER_DIR by 
         <b>path to your <i>SPIDER</i> directory</b>):

         <blockquote>   <kbd>
         setenv SPMAN_DIR  "SPIDER_DIR/man/"   <br>
         setenv SPPROC_DIR "SPIDER_DIR/proc/"  <br>
         </kbd> </blockquote> <p>

         You will also need to tell <i>SPIDER</i> the location of the shared 
         run-time libraries for FFTW. These libraries are  usually placed in: 
         <i>/usr/local/lib</i> 
         </p>
         <dl> 
         <dt> If <i>LD_LIBRARY_PATH</i> is not already set in your startup file add
              the following line to your <i>.cshrc</i> startup file</dt>
         <dd> setenv LD_LIBRARY_PATH /usr/local/lib</dd>
         </p>
         <dt>If <i>LD_LIBRARY_PATH</i> is already set in your startup file add
              the following line to your <i>.cshrc</i> startup file</dt>
         <dd> setenv LD_LIBRARY_PATH $LD_LIBRARY_PATH:/usr/local/lib</dd>
         </dl>
    </li>
    </p> 

    <li> 
    <h4>Memory allocation</h4>
         If your system complains about a lack of swap space, then you will have to 
         increase the swap space on your computer.
         Most SPIDER subroutines now allocate their own
         memory at runtime and no longer use large amounts of statically allocated
         space from the unlabeled common.<p>
    </li>
  </ul>
a240 1
</p>
d242 2
a243 48
<p>
<li><h3><a name="run">RUNNING SPIDER </a></h3>
  <p>
  In the following commands substitute the desired SPIDER version for 
  the <i>"?"</i>.  
  </p>

  <p>
  To run SPIDER in a terminal window:

  <blockquote> <kbd>
  <dl>
  <dt>cd SPIDER_DIR/bin     <br>
  spider?                   <br>
  </dl>
  </kbd> </blockquote>
  </p>

  <p>
  All SPIDER data files must have a three letter extension (or datacode).
  This extension is automatically added by SPIDER.  
  </p>

  <p>
  The SPIDER "RESULTS" files are named <i>results.ext.?</i> where 
  "?" is incremented for existing results file in that directory.
  </p>

  <p>
  SPIDER can be run in the background or submitted as a
  <A href="batch-unix_doc.html">batch</a> using the UNIX 
  <i>"at"</i> command.
  </p>


  If SPIDER does not run and you get an error
  message like: <i> command not found </i> see " 
  <a href="#setting">Setting <i>'spider'</i> command</a>" above to
  ensure that your desired executable is accessible.  <br>

  If the SPIDER does not start running and you get a
  error message about a missing library, then you are 
  missing one or more run-time (shared) libraries.
  
  If SPIDER still does not run 
  please contact us at the address 
  below.  Please send  complete info on what you are trying
  to do, error messages, screen dump, etc.
a244 1
</p>
a245 1
<p>
d247 31
a277 3
  <h3><a name="testing"> TESTING SPIDER</a></h3>
   Some <a href="testing.html">simple tests</a> are available to see if 
   SPIDER is installed correctly.      
a278 1
</p>
a279 1
