<h3><li><a name="INSTALLATION"> INSTALLATION</a></h3>
d72 24
d97 114
a210 40
    <li>   Installation of Executables.
       <ul> 
       <li> Using Precompiled and Linked Executables.<br>
            The <i>SPIDER_DIR/bin</i> directory will contain the following
            executable binary files 
            <i>spider_linux,  spider_linuxfftw, & spidermp_linux</i> 
             for use as follows.  <p>  

	    <table border=3 >  
            <tr><th>SPIDER    </th>       <th>processor               </th></tr>
            <tr><td>spider_linux</td>     <td>GNU/Linux on IA32</td></tr> 
                    
            <tr><td>spider_linuxfftw</td> <td>GNU/Linux on IA32, uses 
                                   <a href="http://www.fftw.org/">FFTW</a></td></tr> 
                    
            <tr><td>spidermp_linux</td>   <td>GNU/Linux on Intel, uses 
                       <a href="http://www.fftw.org/">FFTW</a>, and needs 
                       <a href="http://www.pgroup.com/">PGI</a> run time libraries.</td></tr>                     
	    </table>
             <p>

            In the following commands substitute the desired SPIDER version for 
            the <i>"?"</i>.  <br>
            Use the following commands to run SPIDER in a terminal window:

            <blockquote> <kbd>
            <dl>
            <dt>cd SPIDER_DIR/bin     <br>
            spider?                   <br>
            </dl>
            </kbd> </blockquote>

            If SPIDER does not run and you get an error
            message like: <i> command not found </i> see " 
            <A href="#other"> Other Installation Tasks</a>" below to
            ensure that your desired executable is accessible.  <br>

            If the SPIDER does not start running and you get a
            error message about a missing library, then you are 
            missing one or more run-time (shared) libraries.
d212 26
a237 102
            If SPIDER still does not run 
            please contact us at the address 
            below.  Please send  complete info on what you are trying
            to do, error messages, screen dump, etc. <p>

        <li>   Compiling and Linking SPIDER.<br>
            If you wish to modify SPIDER source code, link SPIDER
            with different libraries, or compile
            SPIDER with different compilation options you may have to compile and
            link the source code on your computer.  <br>

            See <A href="compiles.html">SPIDER Compilation and Linking</a>
            for some information on compilation of SPIDER.
        </ul><p>

   <li>   Other Installation Tasks.
         <a name="other">
     
       <ul> 
       <li> Setting "spider" Command.
            You can define an alias for your SPIDER location.  If you 
            are using the 'C' shell, you would put a line similar to 
            the following in your <i>.cshrc</i> startup file, depending on the
            version of SPIDER you intend to use:
            <blockquote>  <kbd>
                alias  spider       SPIDER_DIR/bin/spider?  <br>
            </kbd> </blockquote>

            Alternatively, you can modify your path so that your 
            your system can locate the executable file when you type 
            "spider".  To alter your path add the following to the <i>PATH</i> 
            environmental variable in your startup file: 
            <blockquote> <kbd>
               SPIDER_DIR/bin            <br>
            </kbd> </blockquote>
            then rename the <i>spider?</i> executable in 
            <i>SPIDER_DIR/bin</i> to: <i>spider</i>. <p>
 
       <li> Setting environment variables.    <br>
            Set environment variables for the location of your 
            <i>*.sys, *.man,</i> and <i>"Nextresult"</i> files. 
            (<i>Nextresult</i> is a shell 
            command file which increments the version number on the 
            <i>RESULTS </i> file created by Unix SPIDER).  If you are 
            using the <i>'C'</i> shell, you should put lines 
            similar to the following in your <i>.cshrc</i> startup file:

            <blockquote>   <kbd>
            setenv SPMAN_DIR  "SPIDER_DIR/man/"   <br>
            setenv SPPROC_DIR "SPIDER_DIR/proc/"  <br>
            </kbd> </blockquote> 

       <li> Memory allocation.<br>
            The main memory allocation for the SPIDER system is in the 
            unlabeled common.  This is defined by the size of MAXDI in 
            <A href="../src/spider.f">spider.f</a>.  If your system 
            complains about a lack of swap space, then you will have to 
            increase the swap space on your computer.  A less satisfactory
            alternative is to edit <i>spider.f</i> to decrease MAXDI, 
            and remake your SPIDER system. 
            SPIDER is distributed with a unlabeled common size of 28 Mb. 
            Many SPIDER subroutines now allocate their own
            memory at runtime and no longer use large amounts of space from
            the unlabeled common.<p>
       </ul>

     </ul>

<h3><li><a name="DOCUMENTATION"> DOCUMENTATION </a></h3>
        There is an <A href="documents.html">overview</a>
        of SPIDER documentation in the file: <i>documents.html</i> in 
        the <i>SPIDER_DIR/docs</i> sub-directory.  All SPIDER documentation
        is included with the distribution and is easily accessible via 
        your World-Wide-Web browser (e.g. Netscape).
        Just point your browser at: 
        <A href="master.html">SPIDER_DIR/docs/master.html</a>
        <p>

<h3><li><a name="RUN"> RUNNING SPIDER </a></h3>
        <ul> 
        <li>All SPIDER files must have a three letter extension (or datacode).
           This extension is automatically added by SPIDER.  
        <p>
        <li>The SPIDER "RESULTS" files are named <i>results.ext.?</i> where 
            "?" is incremented for existing results file in that directory.
        <p>
        <li>SPIDER can be run in the background or submitted as a
           <A href="batch-unix_doc.html">batch</a> using the UNIX 
           <i>"at"</i> command.
        <p>

	<li>If the last two characters of a filename
	    consist of a digit followed by a alphabetical character
	    there may be a substitution of a loop
	    counter into the filename. You should avoid such filenames. <p>

        </ul>
        <p>

<h3><li><a name="TESTING"> TESTING SPIDER</a></h3>
        Some  <A href="testing.html">simple tests</a>  are available to see if 
        SPIDER is installed correctly. <p>     
d239 2
a240 2
<h3><li><a name="BUGS"> BUGS, SUGGESTIONS </a></h3>
    <ul> 
